<section id="controls" class="container">

	<div class="container">

		<h2>Controls</h2>

		<p>
			Watercolor provides controls and classes that allow your web application to have a consistent feel for your users. Many controls can have additional class modifiers added to change behavior, such as: <code>primary</code> for default actions, <code>positive</code> for non-destructive actions such as add or save, <code>warning</code> for actions that require user attention, and <code>negative</code> for destructive or error conditions.
		</p>

	</div>
	
	<section id="badge">

		<h3>Badge</h3>
		<p>Use badges for notification counts. A badge can be used inside any element with style <code>position: relative</code>. Include @@mixin <code>badge</code> to turn any <code>span</code> element into a badge. Additional @@mixins are provided to alter the style to change the badge position. Optional styles to provide a <code>badge</code> class, and the various position styles, are provided for convenience.</p>

		<div class="example">

			<span class="badge-image" id="badge-image-1">
				<span class="badge">1</span>
				<img src="/Images/flamebug-Logo-White.png" />
			</span>

			<span class="badge-image" id="badge-image-2">
				<span class="badge bottom-right">2</span>
				<img src="/Images/flamebug-Logo-White.png" />
			</span>

			<span class="badge-image" id="badge-image-3">
				<span class="badge top-left">3</span>
				<img src="/Images/flamebug-Logo-White.png" />
			</span>

			<span class="badge-image" id="badge-image-4">
				<span class="badge bottom-left">4</span>
				<img src="/Images/flamebug-Logo-White.png" />
			</span>

		</div>

		<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-markup">&lt;span class="app"&gt;
   &lt;span class="badge"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="app"&gt;
   &lt;span class="badge bottom-right"&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="app"&gt;
   &lt;span class="badge top-left"&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="app"&gt;
   &lt;span class="badge bottom-left"&gt;4&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;</code></pre>

		<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-css">.app {
    position: relative;
    ...
}
.badge {
	@@include badge;
    &.top-right {
        @@include badge-top-right;
    }
    &.bottom-right {
        @@include badge-bottom-right;
    }
    &.bottom-left {
        @@include badge-bottom-left;
    }
    &.top-left {
        @@include badge-top-left;
    }
}</code></pre>

	</section>

	<section id="button">

		<h3>Button</h3>
		<p>Having consistent button elements throughout your app is important. Include @@mixin <code>button</code> to turn any link into a button. Standard HTML buttons, and input buttons, are styled identically in <a href="/overview#typography">typography.scss</a>. Optional styles to provide a <code>button</code> class, and the various styles and sizes, are provided for convenience.</p>

		<div class="example">

			<a href="#button" class="button">Button</a>
			<a href="#button" class="button" disabled>Button</a>

		</div>

		<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-markup">&lt;a class="button"&gt;Button&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class="button" disabled&gt;Button&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>

		<pre class="example-code"><code class="language-css">.button {
	@@include button;
}</code></pre>

		<p>A button style can be assigned to the button to provide visual clues to the user on the purpose of a button.</p>

		<table>

			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>example</th>
					<th>description</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>

			<tbody>	
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button primary" href="#button">Primary</a></td>
					<td>Primary button style, use for the default form button. Include @@mixin <code>button-primary</code> or use optional class <code>primary</code>.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button positive" href="#button">Positive</a></td>
					<td>Positive, or success, button style, use for positive actions such as saving data. Include @@mixin <code>button-positive</code> or use optional class <code>positive</code>.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button warning" href="#button">Warning</a></td>
					<td>Warning button style, use for actions that require caution from the user. Include @@mixin <code>button-warning</code> or use optional class <code>warning</code>.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button negative" href="#button">Negative</a></td>
					<td>Negative button style, use for actions that delete data. Include @@mixin <code>button-negative</code> or use optional class <code>negative</code>.</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>

		</table>

		<p>Size classes can be added to the button to make it more prominent, or to indicate it is an alternate action such as a cancel button.</p>

		<table>

			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>example</th>
					<th>description</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>

			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button hero" href="#button">Hero</a></td>
					<td>Button sized for hero sections. Include @@mixin <code>button-hero</code> or use optional class <code>hero</code>.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button large" href="#button">Large</a></td>
					<td>Large button to give more emphasis over the default button. Include @@mixin <code>button-large</code> or use optional class <code>large</code>.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button" href="#button">Default</a></td>
					<td>Default button size.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button small" href="#button">Small</a></td>
					<td>Smaller button to give lower emphasis over the default button. Include @@mixin <code>button-small</code> or use optional class <code>small</code>.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><a class="button link" href="#button">Link</a></td>
					<td>Link style button, commonly used for alternate functions such as cancel. Include @@mixin <code>button-link</code> or use optional class <code>link</code>.</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>

		</table>

	</section>
